ii. datetime variables¶

In [10]:
# trans_date_trans_time
df['trans_date'] = df['trans_date_trans_time'].dt.date
df['trans_hour'] = df['trans_date_trans_time'].dt.hour
df['trans_ym'] = df['trans_date_trans_time'].dt.to_period('M')
In [11]:
df['agg'] = 1
df['index'] = df['trans_date_trans_time']
df = df.set_index('index').sort_index()

# rolling: 60 day transaction amount average by card number
df_amt_60d = df.groupby('cc_num')['amt'].rolling('60D').mean().shift().reset_index().fillna(0)
df_amt_60d.columns = ['cc_num','trans_date','avg_amt_60d']
df_amt_60d['trans_date'] = df_amt_60d['trans_date'].dt.date
df_amt_60d = df_amt_60d.groupby(['cc_num','trans_date'])['avg_amt_60d'].min().reset_index()

# rolling: 60 day transactions by card number
df_60d = df.groupby('cc_num')['agg'].rolling('60D').count().shift().reset_index().fillna(0)
df_60d.columns = ['cc_num','trans_date','60d']
df_60d['trans_date'] = df_60d['trans_date'].dt.date
df_60d = df_60d.groupby(['cc_num','trans_date'])['60d'].min().reset_index()

# merge by cc_num, trans_date
df = df.merge(df_amt_60d, left_on = ['cc_num','trans_date'], right_on = ['cc_num','trans_date'], how = 'left')\
    .merge(df_60d, left_on = ['cc_num','trans_date'], right_on = ['cc_num','trans_date'], how = 'left')
df[['avg_amt_60d','60d']]= df[['avg_amt_60d','60d']].fillna(0)
In [12]:
# age = trans_date_trans_time - dob
df['age'] = np.round((df['trans_date_trans_time'] - df['dob'])/np.timedelta64(1,'Y'))

iv. interactive visualizations¶

In [53]:
# amt by city, age, gender
from ipywidgets import interact
import plotly.graph_objects as go

fig = go.FigureWidget()
scatt = fig.add_histogram()

@interact(state=df['state'].unique(), gender=df['gender'].unique(), age=(14,100,5), is_fraud=[0,1])

def update(state='NC',gender='M', age=14, is_fraud=1):
    with fig.batch_update():
        scatt=df[(df['state'] == state) & (df['gender'] == gender) & (df['age'] >= age) & (df['is_fraud'] == is_fraud)]['amt']
        fig.data[0].x=scatt

fig.update_layout(xaxis_title="Transactions", yaxis_title="Transaction Amount")
fig.show()

fraud_oversample = df[df['is_fraud'] == 1].sample(df[df['is_fraud'] == 0]['amt'].count(), replace=True)
df_oversampled = pd.concat([df[df['is_fraud'] == 0], fraud_oversample], axis=0)

iii. train test split¶

In [38]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(df_oversampled[cols], df_oversampled['is_fraud'], train_size=2/3)
In [39]:
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, confusion_matrix, classification_report
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
def model_results(model):
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_train_pred = model.predict(X_train)
    y_test_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    print('train:')
    print(confusion_matrix(y_train, y_train_pred))
    print(classification_report(y_train, y_train_pred))
    print('test:')
    print(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_test_pred))
    print(classification_report(y_test, y_test_pred))
    print(r2_score(y_test, y_test_pred))
    print(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_test_pred, squared=False))
    return model

Summary¶

In this study,we have approximately 1.8 million transaction records with 22 variables. Besides from is_fraud,we have 21 variables to choose as our features.These transactions most occur within United States with a few in Cananda.There is no missing value so we don't need to impute values or delete rows with missing values for this dataset.In order to identify unique entities,we count unique values of city,first name and last name.We find that there are around 1000 customers and 700 merchants in this data.Our target variable is biary but it is imbalance since there are 95 % 0 values and 5% 1 values. In order to deal this issue, we use oversample to select rows in order to make values of 0 and 1 equal.Meanwhile, we find that there are a lot of categorical variables such as gender. So we use onehot encoding to transfer the format of those columns so that they can be feed into our machine learning data. From the correlation map, we can see that amount and 60 average amount are highly correlated with is_fraud. This matches with our knowledge that most frauds are large amount.What is unexpected is that shopping category matters in determine which transaction is fraud.

We have build four models,logistic regression,decision tree,random forests,and xgboost.Logistic Regression tells us how each variable contributes to the probability of the targe.Decesion tree tells us the cretria to split the result. Random Forest are a group of decision trees.Xgboost is black box model.We use confusion matrix to evaluate our models'outcome. They have the following accracy:0.85,0.89,0.89,0.94.These models all perform well and Xgboost is the best model among the four models. However, from the client's bussiness need, we know that they want the model not to be very sensitve so that the customers wont be bothered when they make a purchase and it won't be seen as a fraud.It means we want to find a model with lowest false postive rate.The four models have following FPR:0.115,0.0755,0.0494,0.0409. Since Xgboost has lowest FPR, it is the most suitable model to satisfy client's need.

From the feature importance of XGboost, we can see that category_gas_transport,amt,category_grocery_net are the most important features.What unexpected insight is XGboost is the best model in this case. In most cases, Random Forests would perform better than XGboost in most metrics. In this study, Xgboost actually has hihgest accracy and better R squared and lowest RMSE.
